5335 allocs/op\\n      21\\t  80109865 ns/op\\t  741768 B/op\\t    5334 allocs/op\\n      18\\t  99573975 ns/op\\t 1130583 B/op\\t    8742 allocs/op\\n      18\\t  60853074 ns/op\\t  989642 B/op\\t    8732 allocs/op\\n      20\\t  61361388 ns/op\\t 1226535 B/op\\t    8752 allocs/op\\n      18\\t  66487553 ns/op\\t 1510336 B/op\\t   12441 allocs/op\\n      18\\t  71980194 ns/op\\t 1307464 B/op\\t   12421 allocs/op\\n      16\\t  69224412 ns/op\\t 1518303 B/op\\t   12433 allocs/op\",\"stderr\":\"\",\"interrupted\":false,\"isImage\":false,\"noOutputExpected\":false},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"3e2d3141-212a-40d0-9495-21c98311619d\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"2e211534-959c-4303-8b24-d00364e2665a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"86a4c45c-4c6f-441c-9e41-80eb453d2c7d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/investigate-commit-slowness\",\"slug\":\"optimized-bubbling-widget\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01S2ji2ynHpdy1WeFuPL2i2E\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Good - now I have concrete data. Here's my analysis:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 1: Root Cause Investigation\\n\\n### Benchmark Numbers (Apple M4 Pro, tiny toy repos)\\n\\n| Scenario | Time (ms) | Allocs |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **SingleSession_Active** | 62-72ms | ~5,100 |\\n| **SingleSession_Idle** | 59-80ms | ~5,300 |\\n| **MultipleSessions_2** | 61-100ms | ~8,700 |\\n| **MultipleSessions_3** | 66-72ms | ~12,400 |\\n\\nThese are **synthetic benchmarks on tiny repos** (5 files, 2-line transcripts). Real-world repos have:\\n- Hundreds/thousands of files in the git tree\\n- Large transcripts (thousands of JSONL lines)\\n- Possibly summarization enabled (API call)\\n- Possibly slower disks (spinning, network filesystems)\\n\\nReal-world times are likely **200ms-2s+ for post-commit** and **100ms-1s for prepare-commit-msg** without summarization. With summarization enabled, post-commit could easily be **5-15 seconds**.\\n\\n### Identified Bottlenecks (Ranked)\\n\\n**1. Summarization API call (post-commit)** — `manual_commit_condensation.go:227-256`\\n- `summarize.GenerateFromTranscript()` shells out to `claude` CLI\\n- Blocking network I/O: easily 2-15 seconds\\n- Called per session, synchronously\\n\\n**2. go-git repository open** — `OpenRepository()` in both hooks\\n- Called once per hook invocation\\n- go-git scans `.git/` directory structure on open\\n- On large repos with many refs/objects: 20-100ms\\n\\n**3. Content overlap detection** — `content_overlap.go:47`\\n- `filesOverlapWithContent()` called **redundantly**: once in `sessionHasNewContent`, once in `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck`, and again implicitly in carry-forward\\n- Each call walks git trees + reads transcript files\\n- Pre-resolved `overlapOpts` help, but still called multiple times\\n\\n**4. Session state listing** — `findSessionsForWorktree()`\\n- Reads ALL `.git/entire-sessions/*.json` files\\n- For each session, looks up shadow branch ref to check if orphaned\\n- Called in both `prepare-commit-msg` AND `post-commit` (two full scans per commit)\\n\\n**5. Attribution calculation** — `calculateSessionAttributions()`\\n- Per-file line-level diffs between shadow tree and HEAD\\n- O(files * lines) — scales with session size\\n\\n**6. `WriteCommitted` tree building** — checkpoint store\\n- Builds in-memory git tree + creates commit on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n- go-git plumbing API overhead: hash computation, object storage\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Question 2: Can We Background the Heavy Operations?\\n\\n### What Can Be Backgrounded\\n\\n**post-commit is the primary candidate.** Here's the breakdown:\\n\\n| Operation | Can Background? | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **CondenseSession** | Yes | Core condensation doesn't affect user's working tree |\\n| **Summarization** | Yes (easy win) | Already non-fatal; purely additive metadata |\\n| **Attribution** | Yes | Read-only analysis of committed state |\\n| **WriteCommitted** | Yes | Writes to orphan branch, doesn't affect working tree |\\n| **Shadow branch cleanup** | Yes | Deletes refs, no user-visible effect |\\n| **Session state save** | Partially | Must complete before next hook invocation |\\n\\n**prepare-commit-msg is harder to background** because git blocks on the hook — it must return before the commit editor opens. However, the content-detection phase could be cached from the `SaveStep` call.\\n\\n### Backgrounding Approach\\n\\nThe post-commit hook could:\\n1. Do minimal synchronous work: read HEAD, check for trailer, update `BaseCommit` in session state\\n2. Fork a background process (or goroutine with `os.StartProcess`) for: condensation, attribution, summarization, WriteCommitted, shadow branch cleanup\\n3. Use a lock file (`.git/entire-postcommit.lock`) to prevent concurrent background processes from conflicting\\n\\n### Tradeoffs and Downsides\\n\\n**1. Race conditions with next commit**\\n- If user commits again quickly while background condensation is running, the second post-commit may find stale session state\\n- Mitigation: lock file or queue, but adds complexity\\n\\n**2. Data loss on crash/kill**\\n- If the background process is killed (terminal close, system sleep), condensation data is lost\\n- The shadow branch still has the data, but the `entire/checkpoints/v1` write never happened\\n- Mitigation: the shadow branch acts as a WAL — a recovery sweep could detect uncondensed checkpoints\\n\\n**3. Shadow branch cleanup ordering**\\n- If background condensation hasn't finished but user starts a new turn, SaveStep needs the shadow branch to still exist\\n- Mitigation: defer shadow branch deletion until next successful post-commit (already somewhat the case)\\n\\n**4. Summarization timing**\\n- If backgrounded, the summary won't be available when user runs `entire explain` immediately after committing\\n- Mitigation: show \\\"summary pending...\\\" state, or generate on-demand\\n\\n**5. Session state consistency**\\n- `FullyCondensed`, `TurnCheckpointIDs`, `FilesTouched` updates happen during condensation\\n- If backgrounded, the next `SaveStep` or `PrepareCommitMsg` may see stale state\\n- This is the **hardest problem** — these fields affect whether the next commit gets a trailer\\n\\n**6. Testing complexity**\\n- Background processes are harder to test deterministically\\n- Hook exit code 0 doesn't mean work completed\\n\\n### Recommendation\\n\\nThe **lowest-risk, highest-impact** change would be:\\n\\n1. **Background summarization only** — it's already non-fatal, purely additive, and the easiest to isolate. This alone could save 2-15s for users with summarization enabled.\\n\\n2. **Cache content-detection results** between `PrepareCommitMsg` and `PostCommit` — both hooks call `sessionHasNewContent` / `filesOverlapWithContent`. A short-lived cache (written by prepare-commit, read by post-commit) would eliminate redundant tree walks.\\n\\n3. **Fully background post-commit condensation** is viable but requires careful state synchronization. The key invariant: session state must reflect \\\"condensation pending\\\" so the next prepare-commit-msg doesn't add a duplicate trailer.\\n\\nWant me to dig into any of these approaches further, or start implementing one?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":511,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":102747,\"output_tokens\":1583,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":511,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYfcBpRsCJrhfd4SVutM2\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"3b556da1-3daf-4e67-a2aa-5a46fe7dbf0e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-03T05:38:56.016Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"3b556da1-3daf-4e67-a2aa-5a46fe7dbf0e\",\"isSidechain\