nches, API calls for summarization\\n- Runs within git hook, blocking git completion until finished\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Approach Comparison\\n\\n### Approach 1: os.StartProcess / exec.Command with Special Flag\\n\\n**Implementation Pattern:**\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), executable, \\\"hooks\\\", \\\"git\\\", \\\"post-commit\\\", \\\"--background\\\")\\ncmd.Stdout = io.Discard\\ncmd.Stderr = io.Discard\\n_ = cmd.Start()\\n_ = cmd.Process.Release()  // Allow process to continue independently\\n```\\n\\n**Tradeoffs:**\\n\\n| Factor | Rating | Details |\\n|--------|--------|---------|\\n| **Child survives parent exit** | ✅ Excellent | Yes - starts immediately detached |\\n| **macOS/Linux compatibility** | ✅ Excellent | Works identically on both |\\n| **Git hook behavior** | ✅ Good | Hook returns immediately; hook's 2>/dev/null protects stderr |\\n| **Stdout/stderr handling** | ✅ Good | Explicitly discarded; git hook's 2>/dev/null provides defense-in-depth |\\n| **Signal handling** | ⚠️ Fair | Child has new process ID but inherits parent's signal handlers; unaffected by SIGHUP if using Setpgid |\\n| **Context passing** | ✅ Good | Via command-line args (checkpoint ID, session ID, repo path) |\\n| **Implementation complexity** | ✅ Simple | Straightforward exec.CommandContext call |\\n| **Error reporting** | ⚠️ Fair | Child process failures silent (intentional) - need logging |\\n| **Platform coverage** | ✅ Good | macOS, Linux; Windows requires different approach |\\n\\n**Example Usage:**\\n```go\\n// In PostCommit hook handler\\nif shouldCondenseInBackground() {\\n    go func() {\\n        spawnBackgroundCondense(checkpointID, sessionID, repo.Worktree().Filesystem.Root())\\n    }()\\n    return nil  // Return immediately without waiting\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Codebase Fit:** Excellent - matches existing telemetry pattern exactly\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Approach 2: Goroutine + Syscall.SysProcAttr{Setpgid: true}\\n\\n**Implementation Pattern:**\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), executable, \\\"hooks\\\", \\\"git\\\", \\\"post-commit\\\", \\\"--background\\\")\\ncmd.SysProcAttr = &syscall.SysProcAttr{\\n    Setpgid: true,  // New process group - survives SIGHUP\\n}\\ncmd.Stdout = io.Discard\\ncmd.Stderr = io.Discard\\ngo func() {\\n    _ = cmd.Start()\\n    _ = cmd.Process.Release()\\n}()\\n// Main goroutine returns immediately\\n```\\n\\n**Tradeoffs:**\\n\\n| Factor | Rating | Details |\\n|--------|--------|---------|\\n| **Child survives parent exit** | ✅ Excellent | Yes - new process group survives SIGHUP/SIGTERM |\\n| **macOS/Linux compatibility** | ✅ Excellent | Setpgid works on both; Unix-only but git hooks are Unix |\\n| **Git hook behavior** | ✅ Good | Hook returns; child can run for minutes |\\n| **Stdout/stderr handling** | ✅ Good | Explicitly discarded |\\n| **Signal handling** | ✅ Excellent | Process group isolation means SIGHUP doesn't kill child; clean separation |\\n| **Context passing** | ✅ Good | Via command args (same as Approach 1) |\\n| **Implementation complexity** | ✅ Simple | Adds Setpgid but same structure |\\n| **Error reporting** | ⚠️ Fair | Same as Approach 1 - silent failures, needs logging |\\n| **Platform coverage** | ✅ Good | macOS, Linux; Windows needs CreateProcessGroup |\\n\\n**Key Difference from Approach 1:**\\n- `Setpgid: true` creates new process group, protecting from SIGHUP\\n- Slightly more robust for long-running processes\\n- Default (no Setpgid) still works for post-commit since hook doesn't send signals\\n\\n**Codebase Fit:** Excellent - could be added to telemetry pattern\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Approach 3: Double-Fork Pattern\\n\\n**Implementation Pattern:**\\n```go\\n// First fork\\ncmd1 := exec.Command(os.Args[0], \\\"hooks\\\", \\\"git\\\", \\\"post-commit\\\", \\\"--background\\\")\\ncmd1.SysProcAttr = &syscall.SysProcAttr{Setsid: true}\\nif err := cmd1.Start(); err != nil { return }\\ncmd1.Process.Release()\\n\\n// In child process, second fork happens automatically when parent exits\\n// because process becomes session leader\\n```\\n\\n**Tradeoffs:**\\n\\n| Factor | Rating | Details |\\n|--------|--------|---------|\\n| **Child survives parent exit** | ✅ Excellent | Classic Unix daemon pattern; very reliable |\\n| **macOS/Linux compatibility** | ✅ Excellent | Works on both |\\n| **Git hook behavior** | ⚠️ Fair | Adds complexity for minimal gain over Approach 2 |\\n| **Stdout/stderr handling** | ✅ Good | Same as others |\\n| **Signal handling** | ✅ Excellent | Session leader - completely isolated from TTY signals |\\n| **Context passing** | ✅ Good | Via command args |\\n| **Implementation complexity** | ❌ Complex | Requires understanding Unix daemon model; double-fork pattern outdated |\\n| **Error reporting** | ⚠️ Fair | Silent failures |\\n| **Platform coverage** | ✅ Good | macOS, Linux only |\\n\\n**Why This Is Overkill:**\\n- Go's `exec.CommandContext` with `Setpgid: true` (Approach 2) achieves same isolation\\n- Double-fork pattern is classical Unix but unnecessary in modern Go\\n- No additional benefit over Approach 2 for your use case\\n- More complex implementation, harder to test and debug\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Skip this - Approach 2 is simpler and equally robust\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Approach 4: Job Queue File + Separate Daemon\\n\\n**Implementation Pattern:**\\n```\\n├── .entire/jobs/\\n│   └── post-commit-condense-{sessionID}-{timestamp}.json\\n└── Separate daemon process listening to .entire/jobs/\\n```\\n\\n**Job File Schema:**\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"type\\\": \\\"post-commit-condense\\\",\\n  \\\"checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\",\\n  \\\"session_id\\\": \\\"2026-01-13-uuid\\\",\\n  \\\"repo_root\\\": \\\"/path/to/repo\\\",\\n  \\\"timestamp\\\": 1234567890\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Tradeoffs:**\\n\\n| Factor | Rating | Details |\\n|--------|--------|---------|\\n| **Child survives parent exit** | ✅ Excellent | Daemon is independent; jobs persist on disk |\\n| **macOS/Linux compatibility** | ✅ Excellent | File-based, platform-agnostic |\\n| **Git hook behavior** | ✅ Excellent | Hook returns immediately; zero subprocess overhead |\\n| **Stdout/stderr handling** | ✅ Perfect | No subprocess spawning means no output issues |\\n| **Signal handling** | ✅ Excellent | Daemon independent of hook process signals |\\n| **Context passing** | ✅ Good | JSON files on disk - structured, inspectable |\\n| **Implementation complexity** | ❌ Very Complex | Requires daemon, job queue logic, cleanup, retries |\\n| **Error reporting** | ✅ Good | Job files persist - can inspect failures; needs daemon logging |\\n| **Platform coverage** | ✅ Excellent | Works everywhere (but overkill for Unix) |\\n| **Reliability** | ⚠️ Fair | Job queueing adds failure modes: disk full, stale jobs, race conditions |\\n| **Observability** | ✅ Good | Jobs are on disk; can inspect with `ls .entire/jobs/` |\\n\\n**Operational Complexity:**\\n- Need daemon startup on `entire enable`\\n- Job cleanup strategy (successful jobs deleted; failed jobs retained for inspection)\\n- Concurrent job processing (multiple hooks firing at once)\\n- Zombie jobs from crashes (need TTL-based cleanup)\\n- Restart-safe: daemon can discover jobs on startup\\n\\n**When This Pattern Makes Sense:**\\n- ✅ Cross-platform requirement (Windows + macOS + Linux)\\n- ✅ Multiple hooks producing work (pre-push hooks, agent hooks)\\n- ✅ Wants durable job history/inspection capability\\n- ✅ Needs sophisticated retry logic and failure handling\\n\\n**For Your Use Case:**\\n- ❌ Overkill - Unix hook is already fire-and-forget\\n- ❌ Adds daemon complexity during startup\\n- ❌ File I/O overhead vs subprocess overhead\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Recommendation Matrix\\n\\n| Requirement | Approach 1 | Approach 2 | Approach 3 | Approach 4 |\\n|------------|-----------|-----------|-----------|-----------|\\n| **Simplicity** | 1st ✅ | 1st ✅ | 3rd | 4th ❌ |\\n| **Reliability** | 2nd | 1st ✅ | 1st ✅ | 2nd |\\n| **Matches codebase** | 1st ✅ | 1st ✅ | 2nd | 3rd |\\n|