widget\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"is there a 'manual commit in between' scenario?\"},\"uuid\":\"46d8370d-f285-4c8f-bafb-ba602fa06d52\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T00:09:41.056Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"plan\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"46d8370d-f285-4c8f-bafb-ba602fa06d52\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"86a4c45c-4c6f-441c-9e41-80eb453d2c7d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/investigate-commit-slowness\",\"slug\":\"optimized-bubbling-widget\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01SNXo91R1Tyf1CRqB53aZ48\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user is asking about a scenario where the user makes multiple commits during a session without the agent doing anything in between. Let me think about this...\\n\\nIf the user makes commit A, then condensation runs, AttributionBaseCommit is updated to commit A. Then the user makes commit B — AttributionBaseCommit = commit A = HEAD~1. Same thing, no divergence.\\n\\nBut what about: agent works, user makes commit A (condensation runs, AttributionBaseCommit = A), user makes commit B WITHOUT any agent work in between. Would condensation run again?\\n\\nLet me check — PostCommit fires for every commit. It checks if there are active sessions. If the session is IDLE and has no new content, would it still condense?\\n\\n\\nNow I'm tracing through what happens when the PostCommit hook runs but there's no new agent content — it looks for the checkpoint trailer first, and if PrepareCommitMsg didn't add one because there was no session activity, it exits early. The trickier scenario is when the user makes a partial commit of agent-modified files, like if the agent worked on files A, B, and C but the user only stages and commits A and B — that would trigger condensation with a new AttributionBaseCommit.\\n\\nBut the real problem emerges when commits happen without agent involvement: if the user makes a commit with no agent content, the trailer doesn't get added, so PostCommit returns early and AttributionBaseCommit stays at its previous value. Then when the agent works again and the user commits, AttributionBaseCommit is now several commits behind HEAD, meaning the baseTree is stale and doesn't reflect the actual state of the repository. the user is asking about! A manual commit in between that doesn't trigger condensation.\\n\\nIn this case, `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees(baseTree=commit1, headTree=commit3)` would find files changed across commits 2 AND 3, while `filesChangedInCommit(HEAD~1=commit2, HEAD=commit3)` would only find files changed in commit 3.\\n\\nThe attribution would need to account for files the user changed in commit 2 as well, because those happened during the session. If we just used `committedFileSet`, we'd miss the user's non-agent edits from commit 2.\\n\\nSo there IS a valid reason for the divergence! The question is whether this scenario actually happens and whether the attribution needs to be correct across it.\\n\\nWhen the user makes commit 2 with no agent content, the prep and commit message checks run but find no overlap with agent content, so no trailer gets added and PostCommit skips early. The AttributionBaseCommit stays at commit1. Then when commit 3 happens, the diff between commit1 and commit3 captures changes from both commits 2 and 3, which is intentional—it ensures all user work during the session gets counted. If I switched to just using the committed file set from commit 3, I'd miss the user's edits from commit 2 and artificially inflate the agent's percentage.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":266,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":112836,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":266},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYh4wr1sXv8dhXdGmUUdh\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"d26d2cd8-924d-4715-b135-18c83fa8eb9b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T00:10:07.392Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"d26d2cd8-924d-4715-b135-18c83fa8eb9b\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"86a4c45c-4c6f-441c-9e41-80eb453d2c7d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/investigate-commit-slowness\",\"slug\":\"optimized-bubbling-widget\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01SNXo91R1Tyf1CRqB53aZ48\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yes. Consider this:\\n\\n1. Agent works, user commits → condensation runs, `AttributionBaseCommit` = commit A\\n2. User makes a **manual commit** (their own files, no agent content) → PrepareCommitMsg sees no content overlap, no trailer added → PostCommit skips → `AttributionBaseCommit` stays at commit A\\n3. Agent works more, user commits → `AttributionBaseCommit` = commit A, but HEAD~1 = commit B\\n\\nNow `baseTree` (commit A) ≠ `parentTree` (commit B). The `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees(baseTree, headTree)` would span commits B and C, catching the user's non-agent file edits from commit B that were never attributed. `filesChangedInCommit` would only see commit C.\\n\\nSo `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees` is actually doing something meaningful here — it ensures user work from the \\\"gap\\\" commit is counted in attribution, preventing the agent percentage from being inflated.\\n\\nThat means we **can't** just substitute `committedFileSet` directly. We need the broader base→HEAD range for non-agent files. The question is how to do that efficiently.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":266,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":112836,\"output_tokens\":1227,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fe